The theory of relativity is a scientific explanation of how time and space are related. It was first introduced by Albert Einstein in the early 20th century and it has since become one of the most important theories in physics.

There are two parts to the theory of relativity: the special theory of relativity and the general theory of relativity.

The special theory of relativity says that the laws of physics are the same for everyone, no matter how fast they are moving or in which direction. It also says that time and space are not absolute, but are relative to the observer. This means that
